body:
Unfortunate Is Unfortunate Delayed Update Explaination

I’m so sorry I haven’t been posting lately on here. I know some of you are waiting for Part 2 of Unfortunate is Unfortunate. (The tag list is still open)

I’ve just been enjoying my summer with my family and relatives who came to visit. Also, I have books (on my Wattpad account) that need some updating and editing.

But, I did plan to post the 2nd part of Unfortunate is Unfortunate late last week but after reading it I didn’t like it at all. So I scrapped it and started a new one which I’m only about 500+ words into.

To make it up to all of you I’ll post a teaser when I think the next Part is almost ready for reveal and give an exact date of publication.

summary: Amazing Spider-Man #252 (May 1984) When I found out Spider-Man would be getting a new costume I was really excited. It looked...
caption:
Amazing Spider-Man #252 (May 1984)

When I found out Spider-Man would be getting a new costume I was really excited. It looked sleek and bad-ass!  Furthermore, I was certain the issue would be valuable in no time!  So Amazing Spider-Man #252 became the first comic (and maybe the only to this day?) of which I bought TWO COPIES off the newsstand. I planned to keep one for reading and store the other to keep in mint condition.

I don’t know whatever happened to the one that was supposed to be “mint.” I may have sold it in the 90s or even given it away to a friend.

What I remember most about getting this comic is two things:

1) I got it at a luncheonette on the corner of 5th avenue and 39th street (I think that was the cross street) in Sunset Park Brooklyn. It had a spinner rack, but was mostly patronized by bus drivers and other MTA workers because of the nearby depot. When I brought two copies of the comic to the counter to pay for them, the guy ringing me up said, “You have two of the same comic book here,” thinking he was pointing out a mistake to me.  “I know,” I replied.

“Getting one for a friend?”

“Nope.”

He looked at me quizzically (I didn’t want to say it would be valuable. b/c what if he changed his mind about selling it to me!?).  I then asked for a bag and he scoffed, “Get the heck out of here, kid! A bag? For a lousy comic book? Gimme a break!”  I hurried out and ended up putting the comic books in my loose-leaf binder to try to keep them flat.

2) The actual story in this comic book is not very good.
